# Response DTO Patterns

## 📌 PURPOSE

Defines rules for Response DTOs used for outgoing API responses.

---

## 📂 LOCATION

### DO

* Place all response DTOs in:

```id="x4l9de"
dto/response
```

---

## 🔵 STRUCTURE

### DO

* Include only fields required by client
* Keep structure flat and simple

### EXAMPLE

```java id="k8z3mn"
public class TaskResponse {

    private Long id;
    private String title;
    private String description;
    private String status;
}
```

---

## ⚠️ DATA EXPOSURE RULES

### DO

* Expose only necessary data

### DO NOT

* Do not expose:

  * Internal IDs (if sensitive)
  * Database fields not needed
  * Audit/internal fields

---

## 🔄 MAPPING RULES

### DO

* Map Entity → Response DTO in service layer

### EXAMPLE

```java id="7y2lqp"
TaskResponse response = new TaskResponse();
response.setId(task.getId());
response.setTitle(task.getTitle());
```

---

## 📊 COLLECTION RESPONSE

### DO

* Use wrapper for lists (optional but recommended)

### EXAMPLE

```java id="v9c8as"
public class TaskListResponse {

    private List<TaskResponse> data;
}
```

---

## 🧾 STATUS FIELD

### DO

* Include status where relevant

### EXAMPLE

```java id="d2h7qk"
private String status;
```

---

## 🚫 DO NOT RULES

* Do not return entity objects
* Do not include sensitive fields
* Do not include request-only fields

---

## ⚙️ BEST PRACTICES

### DO

* Keep naming consistent:

  * TaskResponse
* Keep responses predictable
* Follow API design rules

---

## 🧠 AI ENFORCEMENT RULES

* MUST use response DTO for all responses
* MUST NOT expose entities
* MUST map in service layer
* MUST keep response minimal

